I"çT<p>Context-free grammars find applications in many programming languages. In this series, we discuss theoretical underpinnings of context-free grammars and the associated family of languages.</p>

<p>We begin by introducing the notion of rewriting systems and grammars.</p>

<p><strong>Definition 1 (Rewriting System): A rewriting system is a 2-tuple <script type="math/tex">(\Sigma, P)</script> such that</strong></p>

<p><strong>(1) <script type="math/tex">\Sigma</script> is an alphabet</strong></p>

<p><strong>(2) <script type="math/tex">P</script> is a finite set of productions, each of which is of the form <script type="math/tex">p_i \rightarrow q_i</script> where <script type="math/tex">p_i, q_i</script> are words in <script type="math/tex">\Sigma^*</script></strong></p>

<p>With a rewriting system <script type="math/tex">R</script>, we say a word <script type="math/tex">v</script> is <em>directly derived</em> from the word <script type="math/tex">w</script>, written as</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">w \Rightarrow_R v</script>

<p>,if <script type="math/tex">w</script> is of the form <script type="math/tex">rp_is</script> and <script type="math/tex">v=rq_is</script> for some production <script type="math/tex">p_i \rightarrow q_i</script>. Furthremore, we say a word <script type="math/tex">v</script> is derived from the word <script type="math/tex">w</script>, written as</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">w \Rightarrow_R^* v</script>

<p>, if there exists a finite sequence of <script type="math/tex">w_1,...,w_n</script> such that</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">w \Rightarrow_R w_1 \Rightarrow_R ... \Rightarrow_R w_n \Rightarrow_R v</script>

<p>Sometimes we ignore the the underscript <script type="math/tex">R</script> if the context is clear.</p>

<p>With the notion of derivation, the language generated by a word <script type="math/tex">w</script> in a rewriting system <script type="math/tex">R</script> is</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">L(R, w) = \{ v \ | \ w \Rightarrow_R^* v \}</script>

<p>Grammars are special types of rewriting systems such that the alphabet is divided into a variable alphabet and a constant alphabet, and specify a variable symbol as the starting symbol.</p>

<p><strong>Definition 2 (Grammar): A grammar is a quadruple <script type="math/tex">(\Sigma_V, \Sigma_C, X_0, P)</script> such that</strong></p>

<p><strong>(1) <script type="math/tex">\Sigma_V</script> is an alphabet of variable symbols</strong></p>

<p><strong>(2) <script type="math/tex">\Sigma_C</script> is an alphabet of constant symbols</strong></p>

<p><strong>(3) <script type="math/tex">X_0 \in \Sigma_V</script> is the starting symbol, also called the axiom</strong></p>

<p><strong>(4) <script type="math/tex">P</script> is a finite set of productions, each of which is of the form <script type="math/tex">p_i \rightarrow q_i</script>, where <script type="math/tex">p_i, q_i</script> are words in <script type="math/tex">(\Sigma_V \cup \Sigma_C)^*</script>, and there is at least one variable symbol in <script type="math/tex">p_i</script></strong></p>

<p>Variable and constant symbols are also called nonterminal and terminal symbols. In the remaining discussion, we use upper-case letters such as <script type="math/tex">X, Y, Z</script> to denote variable symbols, and lower-case letters such as 
<script type="math/tex">a, b, c</script> to denote constant variables. Also for convenience, we use <script type="math/tex">\Sigma = \Sigma_V \cup \Sigma_C</script> to denote the whole alphabet.</p>

<p>Note that a production like <script type="math/tex">a \rightarrow XYb</script> is not allowed in a grammar, as it contains no variable symbol on the left-hand side.</p>

<p>For a grammar <script type="math/tex">G</script>, the language generated by <script type="math/tex">G</script> 
is <script type="math/tex">L(G) = \{ w \in \Sigma_C^* \ | \ X_0 \Rightarrow_G^* w\}</script>, i.e. the words formed by constant variables and derivable from the starting symbol <script type="math/tex">X_0</script>.</p>

<p>Different types of grammars would generate different family of languages. There are four types of grammars, and they form the Chomsky Hierarchy. N</p>

<p><strong>Type-0 (CE)</strong>: No restriction on <script type="math/tex">P</script></p>

<p><strong>Type-1 (CS)</strong>: Context-sensitive grammars. Each production is of the form <script type="math/tex">u_i X_i v_i \rightarrow u_i w_i v_i</script>, where <script type="math/tex">u_i, v_i \in \Sigma^*</script>, and <script type="math/tex">w_i \in \Sigma^+</script>. We require that <script type="math/tex">w_i</script> cannot be 
the empty word <script type="math/tex">\epsilon</script>. The only exception is the production <script type="math/tex">X_0 \rightarrow \epsilon</script> provided that there is no production where <script type="math/tex">X_0</script> appear on the right-hand side.</p>

<p><strong>Type-2 (CF)</strong>: Context-free grammars. Each production is of the form <script type="math/tex">X_i \rightarrow w_i</script>. That is, there is only one single variable symbol on the left-hand side for any production. The rewriting of <script type="math/tex">X_i</script> does 
not depend on any context.</p>

<p><strong>Type-3 (Linear)</strong>: Linear grammars. Each production is of the form <script type="math/tex">X_i \rightarrow w_i</script>, where <script type="math/tex">w_i</script> contains at most one variable symbol.</p>

<p>In can be shown that <script type="math/tex">Linear \subset CF \subset CS \subset CE</script>$.</p>

<p>The languages in each family are closed under some common language operations, such as union, concatenation, Kleene star, etc. The details will be discussed in the future.</p>

<p>There is another type of grammars, called <strong>length-increasing grammar</strong>, which geneartes a word of increasing length in any derivation. Specifically,</p>

<p><strong>Length-increasing Gramma:</strong> Each production rule is of form <script type="math/tex">p_i \rightarrow q_i</script>, where <script type="math/tex">|p_i| \leq |q_i|</script>. Again like CS, we allow the exception that <script type="math/tex">X_0 \rightarrow \epsilon</script>, provided that there is no 
production where <script type="math/tex">X_0</script> appears on the right-hand side.</p>

<p>It is easily seen that</p>

<p><strong>Lemma 3: Context-sensitive grammar <script type="math/tex">\subseteq</script> Length-increasing gramma</strong></p>

<p><em>Proof</em>: In a context-sensitive grammar, each production is of the form <script type="math/tex">u_i X_i v_i \rightarrow u_i w_i v_i</script>, where <script type="math/tex">w_i</script> cannot be the empty word. Therefore <script type="math/tex">|w_i| \geq 1</script> and <script type="math/tex">|u_i X_i v_i| \leq |u_i w_i v_i|</script>.
<script type="math/tex">\tag*{$\blacksquare$}</script></p>

<p>The converse is also true. Before proving this claim, letâ€™s prove a useful lemma.</p>

<p><strong>Lemma 4 (Removing constants on left-hand side): For any grammar <script type="math/tex">G</script>, there exists a grammar <script type="math/tex">G'</script>, whose productions contain no constant variable on the left-hand sides, such that <script type="math/tex">L(G) = L(G')</script>.</strong></p>

<p><em>Proof:</em> For any grammar <script type="math/tex">G = (\Sigma_V, \Sigma_C, X_0, P)</script>, we construct a grammar <script type="math/tex">G'</script> as follows. For each constant symbol <script type="math/tex">a \in \Sigma_C</script>, create a â€śshadowâ€ť symbol <script type="math/tex">a'</script> as a new variable symbol. We call the 
set <script type="math/tex">\Sigma'_C</script> the shadow set of <script type="math/tex">\Sigma_C</script>. Let <script type="math/tex">\Sigma'_V = \Sigma_V \cup \Sigma'_C</script>, i.e. add all shadow variables into the original variables. So we create the new grammar <script type="math/tex">G' = (\Sigma'_V, \Sigma_C, X_0, P')</script>
, where the new productions <script type="math/tex">P'</script> are created as follows.</p>

<p>First, <script type="math/tex">P'</script> contains all the productions in <script type="math/tex">P</script> except the ones whose left-hand sides contain constants. Next, for a production <script type="math/tex">p_i \rightarrow q_i</script> containing constants on left-hand side, we replace each constant 
<script type="math/tex">a</script> with its shadow variable <script type="math/tex">a'</script>, and add productions <script type="math/tex">a' \rightarrow a</script>. After adding these rules, the resulting <script type="math/tex">P'</script> is the set of productions in <script type="math/tex">G'</script>.</p>

<p>It is easy to see that if <script type="math/tex">w \Rightarrow_G v</script> then <script type="math/tex">w \Rightarrow_{G'}^* v</script>. So <script type="math/tex">L(G) \subseteq L(G)</script>. Conversely, if <script type="math/tex">w \Rightarrow_{G'}^* v</script>, then the derivation may or may not contain any <script type="math/tex">a' \rightarrow a</script> 
production. If this is the latter case, then <script type="math/tex">w \Rightarrow_G^* v</script>. If this the former case, since the shadow variables only appear in producitons like <script type="math/tex">a' \rightarrow a</script>, we have <script type="math/tex">w \Rightarrow_G^* v</script> as well. 
Therefore, <script type="math/tex">L(G') \subseteq L(G)</script>. <script type="math/tex">\tag*{$\blacksquare$}</script></p>

<p>Now we can proceed to prove</p>

<p><strong>Theorem 5: Length-increasing gramma <script type="math/tex">\subseteq</script> Context-sensitive grammar</strong></p>

<p><em>Proof</em>: Note that length-increasing production only requires <script type="math/tex">|p_i| \leq |q_i|</script>. It makes no assumption about the forms of <script type="math/tex">p_i</script> or <script type="math/tex">q_i</script>. However, productions <script type="math/tex">p_i \rightarrow q_i</script> in a context-sensitive grammar 
requires <script type="math/tex">p_i, q_i</script> to take the forms <script type="math/tex">u_i X_i v_i \rightarrow u_i w_i v_i</script>. Below we prove that every length-increasing rule <script type="math/tex">p_i \rightarrow q_i</script> can be replaced by a finite set of context-sensitive rules.</p>

<p>So consider a length-increasing but not context-sensitive rule <script type="math/tex">p \rightarrow q</script>. By Lemma 4, we can assume that there are no constants in <script type="math/tex">p_i</script>. Thus, <script type="math/tex">p, q</script> are of the forms</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">X_1...X_m \rightarrow Y_1...Y_n</script>

<p>, where <script type="math/tex">n \geq m \geq 2</script> (Note <script type="math/tex">X_1 \rightarrow Y_1Y_2</script> is a context-sensitive rule. Thus <script type="math/tex">m \geq 2</script>.) We create a finite set of new variables <script type="math/tex">Z_1,...,Z_m</script>, and add the following context-sensitive rules:</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">% <![CDATA[
\begin{align}
\underline{X_1}X_2...X_m &\rightarrow \underline{Z_1}X_2...X_m \\
Z_1 \underline{X_2}...X_m &\rightarrow Z_1 \underline{Z_2}...X_m \\
&\vdots \\
Z_1...Z_{m-1}\underline{X_m} &\rightarrow Z_1...Z_{m-1}\underline{Z_m Y_{m+1}...Y_n} \\
\underline{Z_1}Z_2...Z_m Y_{m+1}...Y_n &\rightarrow \underline{Y_1}Z_2...Z_m Y_{m+1}...Y_n \\
&\vdots \\
Y_1...Y_{m-1}\underline{Z_m}Y_{m+1}...Y_n &\rightarrow Y_1...Y_{m-1}\underline{Y_m}Y_{m+1}...Y_n
\end{align} %]]></script>

<p>. The underlines indicate the rewritings. <script type="math/tex">\tag*{$\blacksquare$}</script></p>

<p>By Lemma 3 and Theorem 5, we have</p>

<p><strong>Theorem 6: Context-sensitive Grammars = Length-increasing Grammars</strong></p>

<h2 id="regular-languages-are-type-3-languages">Regular Languages are Type-3 Languages</h2>

<p>We show regular languages are exactly languages generated by type-0 grammars.</p>

<p>A regular language <script type="math/tex">L</script> is equivalent to a DFA <script type="math/tex">M=(\Sigma, Q, q_0, T, \delta)</script>. Since there is only a finite number of states and the alphabet is also finite, we take <script type="math/tex">\Sigma_V = Q</script>, <script type="math/tex">\Sigma_C = \Sigma</script>, 
<script type="math/tex">X_0 = q_0</script> and the productions are: <script type="math/tex">q_i \rightarrow a q_j</script> whenever <script type="math/tex">\delta(q_i, a) = q_j</script>. Finally, for every terminal state <script type="math/tex">q_t \in T</script> we construct a production <script type="math/tex">q_t \rightarrow \epsilon</script>. The resulting 
grammar is type-0 grammar. This process proves</p>

<p><strong>Lemma 6: Regular Language <script type="math/tex">\subseteq</script> Type-3 Language</strong></p>

<p>On the other hand, proving a type-0 language is regular language would require first construct an equivalent type-0 grammar where each production takes the form of either <script type="math/tex">X_1 \rightarrow aY_1</script>, or <script type="math/tex">X_2 \rightarrow Y_2b</script>,
or <script type="math/tex">X_3 \rightarrow \epsilon</script>. The resulting language <script type="math/tex">L</script> is a concatenation of two regular languages <script type="math/tex">L_1L_2</script>, where <script type="math/tex">L_1</script> is generated by a DFA equivalent to all <script type="math/tex">X_1 \rightarrow aY_1</script> rules and <script type="math/tex">L_2</script> all 
<script type="math/tex">X_2 \rightarrow Y_2 b</script> rules. The details are as follows.</p>

<p><strong>Lemma 7: For any type-3 grammar, there is an equivalent type-3 grammar whose productions are either of the form <script type="math/tex">X_1 \rightarrow aY_1</script>, or of the form <script type="math/tex">X_2 \rightarrow Y_2 b</script>, or <script type="math/tex">X_3 \rightarrow Y</script> or 
<script type="math/tex">X_4 \rightarrow a</script>.</strong></p>

<p><em>Proof</em>: The equivalence of two grammars means they generate the same language.</p>

<p>Consider a type-3 grammar <script type="math/tex">G</script>. Suppose its production is of the form <script type="math/tex">X_i \rightarrow u_i Y_i v_i</script>. If there is no production of the form <script type="math/tex">X_j \rightarrow a</script>, then <script type="math/tex">G</script> generates the empty language <script type="math/tex">\emptyset</script>.
In this case, just create the type-3 grammar with only one production <script type="math/tex">X_1 \rightarrow Y_1</script> and it generates <script type="math/tex">\emptyset</script> as well.</p>

<p>In a general case, we construct the set of productions of the forms <script type="math/tex">X'_{i_K} \rightarrow a_{i_k}Y'_{i_k}, X'_{i_j} \rightarrow Y'_{i_j} b_{i_j}</script> to replace the production <script type="math/tex">X_i \rightarrow u_i Y_i v_i</script>. The process is 
as follows. We only need to consider the case when <script type="math/tex">u_i, v_i</script> are not empty.</p>

<p>Second, if <script type="math/tex">u_i = a_1...a_n</script> is not empty, we create <script type="math/tex">n</script> new variables <script type="math/tex">Z_{i,1},...,Z_{i, n}</script> and add rules</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">% <![CDATA[
\begin{align}
X_i &\rightarrow a_1 Z_{i,1} \\
Z_{i, 1} &\rightarrow a_2 Z_{i, 2} \\
&\vdots \\
Z_{i, n-1} &\rightarrow a_n Z_{i, n} \\
Z_{i, n} &\rightarrow Y_i v_i 
\end{align} %]]></script>

<p>Finally, if <script type="math/tex">v_i = b_1...b_m</script> is not empty, we create <script type="math/tex">m-1</script> new variables <script type="math/tex">W_{i, 2},...,W_{i, m}</script> and add rules</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">% <![CDATA[
\begin{align}
Z_{i, n} &\rightarrow W_{i, m} b_m \\
W_{i, m} &\rightarrow W_{i, m-1} b_{m-1} \\
&\vdots \\
W_{i, 2} &\rightarrow Y_i b_1 \\
\end{align} %]]></script>

<p>It is not difficult to show that we obtain the same language by replacing <script type="math/tex">X_i \rightarrow u_i Y_i v_i</script> by these <script type="math/tex">n+m+1</script> new rules.  <script type="math/tex">\tag*{$\blacksquare$}</script></p>

<p><strong>Theorem 8: Type-3 language <script type="math/tex">\subseteq</script> Regular Language</strong></p>

<p><em>Proof</em>: Let <script type="math/tex">L</script> be a type-3 language, and <script type="math/tex">G</script> be an associated type-3 gramma. By Lemma 7, we may assume the rule in <script type="math/tex">G</script> is either of the form <script type="math/tex">X \rightarrow u Y</script>, 
or of the form <script type="math/tex">X \rightarrow Y v</script>, or of the form <script type="math/tex">X \rightarrow Y</script>, or of the form <script type="math/tex">X \rightarrow a</script>. If a word <script type="math/tex">w \in L</script>, it can be written the concatenation of two sub-words (possibly empty) <script type="math/tex">w_1 w_2</script> such that 
<script type="math/tex">w_1</script> is generated by applying rules of the form <script type="math/tex">X \rightarrow uY</script> while <script type="math/tex">w_2</script> is generated by applying the rules of form <script type="math/tex">X \rightarrow Yv</script>. We call <script type="math/tex">w_1, w_2</script> the left word and right word of <script type="math/tex">w</script>, respectively.
Let <script type="math/tex">L_1 = \{ w_1 \ | \ w = w_1 w_2 \ and \ w \in L \}</script>. (by proper set theory language, the set <script type="math/tex">L_1</script> is valid.) That is, <script type="math/tex">L_1</script> is the language consisting of all the left words in <script type="math/tex">L</script>. 
Similarly, let <script type="math/tex">L_2</script> be the language consisting of all the right words. Then <script type="math/tex">L = L_1 \cdot L_2</script>. If <script type="math/tex">L_1, L_2</script> are regular, then <script type="math/tex">L</script> is regular. The key idea is to construct a DFA <script type="math/tex">M_1</script> that recognizes <script type="math/tex">L_1</script>,
and another DFA <script type="math/tex">M_2</script> that recognizes <script type="math/tex">\hat{L_2}</script>, which is the mirror language of <script type="math/tex">L_2</script>. Since the mirror of a regular language is also regular, <script type="math/tex">L_2</script> is regular.  Therefore, 
it remains to construct the two DFAs <script type="math/tex">M_1</script> and <script type="math/tex">M_2</script> for our proof.</p>

<p>Letâ€™s first construct a directed graph <script type="math/tex">M</script> using the rules in <script type="math/tex">G</script>. Eeach variable is a vertex in the graph. In addition, we create a terminal vertex <script type="math/tex">T</script>. For a rule of the form <script type="math/tex">X \rightarrow uY</script>, create a directed edge from vertex <script type="math/tex">X</script> to vertex <script type="math/tex">Y</script> 
and label the edge with <script type="math/tex">u</script>. In addition, we <em>color the edge blue</em>. For a rule of the form <script type="math/tex">X \rightarrow Y v</script>, create a directed edge from <script type="math/tex">X</script> to <script type="math/tex">Y</script> with the label <script type="math/tex">v</script>. But we color it <em>red</em>. Next, for 
the rule of the form <script type="math/tex">X \rightarrow a</script> we create an edge from <script type="math/tex">X</script> to the terminal vertex <script type="math/tex">T</script>, and label it both blue and red. Finally, for the rule of the form <script type="math/tex">X \rightarrow Y</script>, we create an <script type="math/tex">\epsilon-</script>edege from 
<script type="math/tex">X</script> to <script type="math/tex">Y</script> in both blue and red.</p>

<p>Next, we construct a <script type="math/tex">\epsilon-NFA</script> from <script type="math/tex">M</script>, which recognizes the language <script type="math/tex">L_1</script> as follows. For any vertex <script type="math/tex">X</script>, let <script type="math/tex">C(X)</script> be the red-closure of <script type="math/tex">X</script>. That is, starting from <script type="math/tex">X</script>, we traverse the graph 
through red edges, and add vertices along the way to <script type="math/tex">C(X)</script>. Since the graph has a finite number of vertices, this traversal will terminate. For a vertex <script type="math/tex">Y</script> in <script type="math/tex">C(X)</script>, if there exists a blud edge starting from <script type="math/tex">Y</script> 
or <script type="math/tex">Y</script> is a terminal state,  then we add a <script type="math/tex">\epsilon-</script> and blue edge from <script type="math/tex">X</script> to <script type="math/tex">Y</script>. So by this process, we create a set of <script type="math/tex">\epsilon-</script> and blue edges. Now by taking <script type="math/tex">X_0</script> as the initial state, all terminal states 
in <script type="math/tex">M</script> as the set of terminal states, and all blue edges as transitions, we construct a <script type="math/tex">\epsilon-</script>NFA <script type="math/tex">M_1</script>. It is not difficult to show that <script type="math/tex">M_1</script> recognizes <script type="math/tex">L_1</script>.</p>

<p>Similary, we can use red edges (adding necessary red edges) to construct another <script type="math/tex">\epsilon-</script>NFA that recognizes <script type="math/tex">\hat{L_2}</script>. This completes our proof. <script type="math/tex">\tag*{$\blacksquare$}</script></p>

<p>With Lemma 6 and Theorem 8, we conclue that</p>

<p><strong>Theorem 9: Regular Language <script type="math/tex">=</script> Type-3 Language</strong></p>

